The Ukraine on the Path to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
Although Ukraine lies undoubtedly in the East, it is in Eastern Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became our dominant goal.
However, the path there was not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 showed that Ukrainians are still determined to go this way.
I am a Social Democrat and have never been a member of the communist party, although as a lawyer during the Soviet Union, I was quite successful.
It is out of the question for me that our 'Soviet' legacy is largely responsible for Ukraine's difficulties in joining Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machine parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture in the Soviet mold.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very burdensome, the pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is massive.
But our Soviet legacy does not justify everything.
We thoroughly botched the reform all on our own.
For often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West – private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of civil society, representative democracy – in watered-down form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Trotz dieser nostalgischen Anwandlungen in der Politik hat der Oberste Rat (das Parlament der Ukraine) im Laufe der Jahre Bürgerrechte und Strafrecht, Land-, Familien und Wirtschaftsrechte verabschiedet, was so etwas wie einer Revolution gleichkommt.
Die Akzeptanz westlicher Werte in einer Gesellschaft, die über Jahrhunderte hinweg von der europäischen Geschichte abgeschnitten war, war zwar oft schmerzlich, ist aber in Schwung gekommen, obwohl wir uns nicht unbedingt als eine typische westliche Nation sehen.
Wir sehen uns selbst als offener, sentimentaler, freundlicher und familienbewusster, aber auch chaotischer und gleichgültiger, manchmal unverantwortlich und faul.
Trotzdem sind wir Europäer.
Das sieht man auf den Straßen und Plätzen von Kiew.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to seek safety from thoughtless drivers).
In Kiev, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can stop and enjoy life.
Youth learn English, German, and French; they can handle computers and surf the internet in the Internet cafes.
But these are merely the ramblings of someone who loves Kiev very much.
The sober eye of the professional politician I am sees more profound changes.
In the last ten years, a development from total rejection of reforms through a policy of half-hearted reforms out of corrupt motives to a gradual introduction of Western practices has taken place.
Administrative reform very clearly reflects this.
Initially, the state reform elicited hostile sentiments among both civil servants and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of public servants began.
This was a "Plan F" reform: it was assumed that the state must shrink, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland manage to thrive despite having large state apparatuses.
For the issue is not just one of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better simply by breaking things with a red pen led us to the second stage of our reform process.
Gradually, the state was reformed in a more sensible manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
The work of the government ministries was stabilized through this.
Initially, the authority transferred to these new areas was somewhat too broad to effectively improve their work.
Now they function more or less normally.
Perhaps Ukrainians get annoyed sometimes by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (albeit unwillingly).
Rational politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of whom we still have far too many - can afford to adopt a indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
The taming of our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
The Ukraine was for too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. Because radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming sense of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to some of the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial leader cannot admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
The more we shed our provincial tendency to defend ourselves, the more open we become to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Im Laufe eines Jahrzehnts haben wir vielleicht selbst dazu beigetragen, noch kränker zu werden, aber die kürzlich abgehaltenen Wahlen, die die Kommunisten um ihre vorherrschende Position im Obersten Rat gebracht und die Macht der "mächtigen Parteien" um Präsident Kuchma erheblich beschnitten haben, haben unsere provinziellen Radikalen an den Rand der Politik gedrängt.
Die Reformparteien und die europäischen Parteien haben gesiegt.
Als europäische Außenseiter oder jedenfalls als Volk am Rande Europas wollen wir eine Gesellschaft errichten, in der es keine Außenseiter oder Randständigen gibt.
Wie der große und zu dieser Zeit bereits amerikanische Schriftsteller Vladimir Nabokov in den 70er Jahren sagte: "Von allen Errungenschaften der Natur ist die erstaunlichste wahrscheinlich das Überleben des Schwächsten."
Der lange, entbehrungsreiche Weg nach Europa hat einer schwachen neuen Nation geholfen, stark zu werden und zu überleben.
